the client picked up and used also verbally.

57
00:03:48,160 --> 00:03:50,480
And that caught me thinking as a researcher.

58
00:03:50,480 --> 00:03:55,120
And in many experiments with managers and student we found three practices

59
00:03:55,120 --> 00:04:01,280
that I want to share with you that you can use to really reap the power of pictures professionally.

60
00:04:02,240 --> 00:04:04,720
And the first one, my chalk you,

61
00:04:05,760 --> 00:04:08,880
especially the design of physiognodos among you.

62
00:04:09,680 --> 00:04:16,000
If you want visualization, graphic representations to work for you and for collaboration,

63
00:04:17,120 --> 00:04:18,000
make them ugly.

64
00:04:20,400 --> 00:04:22,560
Beauty is the enemy of collaboration.

65
00:04:22,560 --> 00:04:27,200
If something looks too nice, it looks like it doesn't need revision or improvement.

66
00:04:27,200 --> 00:04:28,720
I call this the museum effect.

67
00:04:29,280 --> 00:04:31,920
People just stared and said, yeah, that looks perfect.

68
00:04:31,920 --> 00:04:33,280
And the thinking stops there.

69
00:04:34,160 --> 00:04:37,600
So you want to use the power of provisionality.

70
00:04:37,680 --> 00:04:39,760
You want to signal with your drawings.

71
00:04:39,760 --> 00:04:41,440
This is working progress.

72
00:04:41,440 --> 00:04:43,280
And invite collaboration in this way.

73
00:04:43,280 --> 00:04:45,840
So this is good news for all of us who are terrible at drawing.

74
00:04:47,120 --> 00:04:48,400
So it's not a bug.

75
00:04:48,400 --> 00:04:49,680
It's a feature.

76
00:04:49,680 --> 00:04:54,560
The technical term is low perceived or low perceived finishness.

77
00:04:54,560 --> 00:04:56,080
It looks provisional.

78
00:04:56,080 --> 00:04:58,480
It invites collaboration.

79
00:04:58,480 --> 00:05:01,520
And by the way, banks and telecom companies and

80
00:05:01,520 --> 00:05:03,840
insurance has been using this all along.

81
00:05:03,840 --> 00:05:05,120
It's called pencil selling.

82
00:05:06,080 --> 00:05:08,240
When instead of using shiny slides,

83
00:05:08,240 --> 00:05:11,920
you just sketch something with a pencil for a client, like a product.

84
00:05:12,400 --> 00:05:15,920
In our experiments, we're able to show this actually is much better.

85
00:05:15,920 --> 00:05:17,120
It leads to more sales.

86
00:05:17,120 --> 00:05:20,720
So if you want to harness the power of visualization for collaboration,

87
00:05:21,360 --> 00:05:22,320
make them look ugly.

88
00:05:23,040 --> 00:05:24,240
Make them look provisional.

89
00:05:24,240 --> 00:05:25,840
You sketches and doodles.

90
00:05:25,840 --> 00:05:29,040
And we've shown in our experiments even little tweaks to software

91
00:05:29,040 --> 00:05:33,360
to make it look more sketchy, boost collaboration and creativity.

92
00:05:35,120 --> 00:05:38,400
And this brings me to the second advice I'd like to share with you.

93
00:05:39,680 --> 00:05:42,880
Like my boss, lead with visual metaphors.

94
00:05:43,520 --> 00:05:47,440
Don't just use diagrams, although they are powerful or charts or maps.

95
00:05:48,720 --> 00:05:50,560
Visual metaphors are magical.

96
00:05:51,360 --> 00:05:53,040
They access what people already know.

97
00:05:54,240 --> 00:05:56,640
They bring out new solution ideas.

98
00:05:57,360 --> 00:06:02,160
They make things much more concrete, like a mini red carpet or a red thread.

99
00:06:02,640 --> 00:06:04,080
Let me give you an example.

100
00:06:04,080 --> 00:06:08,560
In a study that we originally did for BMW financial services and then published,

101
00:06:08,560 --> 00:06:16,400
we used the identical strategy of BMW and communicated it to different staff members,

102
00:06:16,400 --> 00:06:17,360
groups.

103
00:06:17,360 --> 00:06:19,920
Once we used standard bullet points slides,

104
00:06:19,920 --> 00:06:21,200
then we used a diagram.

105
00:06:22,000 --> 00:06:28,000
And for the third group, we used the Mount Trail Visual metaphor with the same content

106
00:06:28,000 --> 00:06:28,880
as the other two.

107
00:06:28,880 --> 00:06:29,600
And guess what?

108
00:06:30,480 --> 00:06:35,040
For the group where we visualized through the mountain trail, the strategy,

109
00:06:35,040 --> 00:06:38,240
not only did they remember a lot more, later on.

110
00:06:39,200 --> 00:06:42,480
They were also much more motivated to implement the strategy.

111
00:06:43,920 --> 00:06:50,480
Now, I've never met a four I didn't like, but clearly not all metaphors are equally well suited.

112
00:06:50,480 --> 00:06:54,960
You want to make sure that the metaphor is simpler than what you're trying to explain,

113
00:06:54,960 --> 00:06:57,760
that it's concrete and that people have a connection with it.

114
00:06:57,760 --> 00:06:59,520
And that is hopefully the right connection.

115
00:06:59,520 --> 00:07:05,520
I will never use again the volcano metaphor as I did once for creativity in a country that is

116
00:07:05,520 --> 00:07:07,600
at risk of active volcanoes.

117
00:07:07,600 --> 00:07:10,240
So choose your metaphors well.

118
00:07:10,240 --> 00:07:13,520
